==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wit
<hw>Wit</hw> <pr>(w⟦icr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>inf.</pos> (To) <conjf>Wit</conjf>; <pos>pres. sing.</pos>
<conjf>Wot</conjf>; <pos>pl.</pos> <conjf>Wite</conjf>; <pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Wist(e)</conjf>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Wist</conjf>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Wit(t)ing</conjf>. See the Note
below.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>witen</ets>, pres. <ets>ich wot</ets>,
<ets>wat</ets>, I know (wot), imp. <ets>wiste</ets>, AS.
<ets>witan</ets>, pres. <ets>w⟦amac⟧t</ets>, imp. <ets>wiste</ets>,
<ets>wisse</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>wita</ets>, OS. <ets>witan</ets>,
D. <ets>weten</ets>, G. <ets>wissen</ets>, OHG. <ets>wizzan</ets>, Icel.
<ets>vita</ets>, Sw. <ets>veta</ets>, Dan. <ets>vide</ets>, Goth.
<ets>witan</ets> to observe, <ets>wait</ets> I know, Russ.
<ets>vidiete</ets> to see, L. <ets>videre</ets>, Gr. <?/, Skr.
<ets>vid</ets> to know, learn; cf. Skr. <ets>vid</ets> to find.
<?/<?/<?/<?/. Cf. <er>History</er>, <er>Idea</er>, <er>Idol</er>,
<er>-oid</er>, <er>Twit</er>, <er>Veda</er>, <er>Vision</er>,
<er>Wise</er>, <pos>a.</pos> & <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Wot</er>.]</ety>
<def>To know; to learn.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>wot</xex> and
<xex>wist</xex> alway.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1659 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The present tense was inflected as follows; sing. 1st
pers. <xex>wot</xex>; 2d pers. <xex>wost</xex>, or <xex>wot(t)est</xex>;
3d pers. <xex>wot</xex>, or <xex>wot(t)eth</xex>; pl. <xex>witen</xex>,
or <xex>wite</xex>. The following variant forms also occur; pres. sing.
1st & 3d pers. <xex>wat</xex>, <xex>woot</xex>; pres. pl.
<xex>wyten</xex>, or <xex>wyte</xex>, <xex>weete</xex>, <xex>wote</xex>,
<xex>wot</xex>; imp. <xex>wuste</xex> (Southern dialect); p. pr.
<xex>wotting</xex>. Later, other variant or corrupt forms are found, as,
in Shakespeare, 3d pers. sing. pres. <xex>wots</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Brethren, we do you to <qex>wit</qex> [make you to know] of the
grace of God bestowed on the churches of Macedonia.</q> <rj><qau>2 Cor.
viii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou <qex>wost</qex> full little what thou meanest.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>witen</qex> not what thing we prayen here.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When that the sooth in <qex>wist</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This verb is now used only in the infinitive, <xex>to
wit</xex>, which is employed, especially in legal language, to call
attention to a particular thing, or to a more particular specification
of what has preceded, and is equivalent to <xex>namely</xex>, <xex>that
is to say</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wit
<hw>Wit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>witt</ets>,
<ets>wit</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>wit</ets>, G. <ets>witz</ets>, OHG.
<ets>wizz⟦imac⟧</ets>, Icel. <ets>vit</ets>, Dan. <ets>vid</ets>, Sw.
<ets>vett</ets>. ⟦root⟧133. See <er>Wit</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Mind; intellect; understanding; sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who knew the <qex>wit</qex> of the Lord? or who was his
counselor?</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif (Rom. xi. 34).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A prince most prudent, of an excellent⟦br⟧
And unmatched <qex>wit</qex> and judgment.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will puts in practice what <qex>wit</qex> deviseth.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He wants not <qex>wit</qex> the dander to decline.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mental faculty, or power of the mind; -- used in
this sense chiefly in the plural, and in certain phrases; <as>as, to
lose one's <ex>wits</ex>; at one's <ex>wits'</ex> end, and the
like</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Men's <xex>wittes</xex> ben so dull.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will stare him out of his <qex>wits</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Felicitous association of objects not usually
connected, so as to produce a pleasant surprise; also. the power of
readily combining objects in such a manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The definition of <qex>wit</qex> is only this, that it is a
propriety of thoughts and words; or, in other terms, thoughts and words
elegantly adapted to the subject.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wit</qex> which discovers partial likeness hidden in general
diversity.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wit</qex> lying most in the assemblage of ideas, and putting
those together with quickness and variety wherein can be found any
resemblance or congruity, thereby to make up pleasant pictures in the
fancy.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A person of eminent sense or knowledge; a man of
genius, fancy, or humor; one distinguished for bright or amusing
sayings, for repartee, and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In Athens, where books and <qex>wits</qex> were ever busier than
in any other part of Greece, I find but only two sorts of writings which
the magistrate cared to take notice of; those either blasphemous and
atheistical, or libelous.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Intemperate <qex>wits</qex> will spare neither friend nor foe.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>wit</qex> herself, Amelia weds a <qex>wit</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The five wits</b></col>, <cd>the five senses; also,
sometimes, the five qualities or faculties, <xex>common wit</xex>,
<xex>imagination</xex>, <xex>fantasy</xex>, <xex>estimation</xex>, and
<xex>memory</xex>.</cd> <rj><au>Chaucer. Nares.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But my <qex>five wits</qex> nor my five senses can⟦br⟧
Dissuade one foolish heart from serving thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Ingenuity; humor; satire; sarcasm; irony;
burlesque.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Wit</er>, <er>Humor</er>. <xex>Wit</xex>
primarily meant mind; and now denotes the power of seizing on some
thought or occurrence, and, by a sudden turn, presenting it under
aspects wholly new and unexpected -- apparently natural and admissible,
if not perfectly just, and bearing on the subject, or the parties
concerned, with a laughable keenness and force. ⟦ldquo⟧What I
want,⟦rdquo⟧ said a pompous orator, aiming at his antagonist, ⟦ldquo⟧is
common sense.⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Exactly</xex>!⟦rdquo⟧ was the whispered
reply. The pleasure we find in <xex>wit</xex> arises from the ingenuity
of the turn, the sudden surprise it brings, and the patness of its
application to the case, in the new and ludicrous relations thus flashed
upon the view. <xex>Humor</xex> is a quality more congenial to the
English mind than <xex>wit</xex>. It consists primarily in taking up the
peculiarities of a <xex>humorist</xex> (or eccentric person) and drawing
them out, as Addison did those of Sir Roger de Coverley, so that we
enjoy a hearty, good-natured laugh at his unconscious manifestation of
whims and oddities. From this original sense the term has been widened
to embrace other sources of kindly mirth of the same general character.
In a well-known caricature of English reserve, an Oxford student is
represented as standing on the brink of a river, greatly agitated at the
sight of a drowning man before him, and crying out, ⟦ldquo⟧O that I had
been <xex>introduced</xex> to this gentleman, that I might save his
life!⟦rdquo⟧ The ⟦ldquo⟧Silent Woman⟦rdquo⟧ of Ben Jonson is one of the
most <xex>humorous</xex> productions, in the original sense of the term,
which we have in our language.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Witan</ent>⟦br⟧
